The paper deals with regular languages and their complexity properties, which are typically studied in the formal language theory (cs.FL) sub-category. The use of different alphabets in binary operations suggests a connection to data structures (cs.DS), while the study of the syntactic semigroup and quotient complexity of atoms suggests a connection to algebraic structures (cs.DM). The use of arguments with different alphabets also suggests a connection to computational complexity (cs.CC), as this technique is often used to obtain tighter upper bounds. Finally, the study of complexity measures such as state and quotient complexity suggests a connection to logic (cs.LO).
